flowRoot.flowPara: The GNOME Project relies on donations in order to carry out its mission. These donations are use to pay for essential maintanence work on our development infrastructure, and is used to pay for important working events, which enable contributors to meet in person and plan for the future.
By donating to GNOME, you can help us to carry on our work, to produce software that works in the interests of users everywhere.
This is the best way to support the GNOME Project, since they provide us with a predictable income. By becoming a subscriber, you can join the Friends of GNOME scheme.
If you'd prefer not to sign up to a monthly subscription, you can still provide a one time donation. Every contribution is greatly appreciated, and helps us with our work.

flowRoot.flowPara: Make a regular donation to the GNOME Project, and join our Friends of GNOME scheme. Friends of GNOME provides vital support to GNOME, enabling us to hold events, bring contributors together, and carry out essential maintanence work on our infrastructure. Without Friends of GNOME, the GNOME Project couldn't exist as it does today.

Hackfests are an essential part of how the GNOME Project works. These events enable contributors to get together to do work and to plan for the future. There is no substitute for meeting to work face-to-face.
In 2013, Friends of GNOME sponsored XXX contributors to attend XX hackfests throughout the world. We need your donations to enable these events to continue.

GNOME's conferences are another essential part of how the project works, which would not be possible without Friends of GNOME. These events give the project an opportunity to get together, share our experiences, and decide on the direction of the project.
In 2013, Friends of GNOME helped us to sponsor XXX people to attend GNOME conferences throughout the world. Your donation will help us to bring even more people together at these important events.

The GNOME Project could not operate without its development infrastructure. These systems are independently maintained by the project, and require a lot of time and effort to improve and keep running.
Donating to Friends of GNOME enables us to keep our infrastructure running, and improve it so we can develop our software even more efficiently.
Have you ever donated to GNOME in the past?
